14 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
15 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 1 O.S. 2021, Section 22, as
amended by Section 1, Chapter 85, O.S.L. 2023 (1 O.S. Supp. 2025,
16 Section 22), is amended to read as follows:
17 Section 22. A. There is hereby re-created to continue until
July 1, 2026, in accordance with the Oklahoma Sunset Law, the
18 Oklahoma Abstractors Board. Beginning January 1, 2008, the Oklahoma
Abstractors Board shall have the total responsibility of
19 administering and enforcing the Oklahoma Abstractors Act.
20 B. The Board shall have the power and duty to prescribe,
promulgate and implement rules as deemed necessary to implement all
21 the provisions of the Oklahoma Abstractors Act.
22 C. The Board shall have the power and duty to obtain and secure
an office in Oklahoma City, and employ, direct, discharge, and
23 define the duties and set the salaries of employees of the Board,
including an executive director, as are necessary to implement the
24 provisions of the Oklahoma Abstractors Act.
Req. No. 17604 Page 5

1
D. The Board shall consist of nine (9) members who shall be
2 appointed by the Governor and confirmed by the Senate:
3 1. Six of the members shall be residents of this state who are
either a holder of a current valid Certificate of Authority or an
4 employee of a holder of a current valid Certificate of Authority for
not less than five (5) years in a county in the district from which
5 the member is appointed prior to appointment. One member shall be
appointed from each of the following districts:
6
District 1: Alfalfa, Beaver, Blaine, Cimarron, Custer, Dewey,
7 Ellis, Garfield, Grant, Harper, Kingfisher, Major, Roger Mills,
Texas, Woods, and Woodward Counties.
8
District 2: Beckham, Caddo, Carter, Comanche, Cotton, Garvin,
9 Grady, Greer, Harmon, Jackson, Jefferson, Kiowa, Love, McClain,
Murray, Stephens, Tillman, and Washita Counties.
10
District 3: Canadian, Cleveland, Logan, and Oklahoma Counties.
11
District 4: Adair, Cherokee, Craig, Delaware, Kay, Mayes,
12 Muskogee, Noble, Nowata, Okmulgee, Osage, Ottawa, Pawnee, Payne,
Sequoyah, and Washington Counties.
13
District 5: Creek, Lincoln, Rogers, Tulsa, and Wagoner Counties.
14
District 6: Atoka, Bryan, Choctaw, Coal, Haskell, Hughes,
15 Johnston, Latimer, LeFlore, McIntosh, Marshall, McCurtain, Okfuskee,
Pittsburg, Pontotoc, Pottawatomie, Pushmataha, and Seminole
16 Counties;
17 2. One member shall be a resident of this state who has been a
licensed real estate broker in Oklahoma for not less than five (5)
18 years;
19 3. One member shall be an attorney who is a resident of this
state who has been licensed to practice in Oklahoma for not less
20 than five (5) years; and
21 4. One member shall be a resident of this state who has been an
officer in a bank in Oklahoma for not less than five (5) years.
22
E. The Governor shall make the initial appointments to the
23 Board within ninety (90) days of July 1, 2007:
24
Req. No. 17604 Page 6

1 1. The initial appointments for the members of the Board shall
be as follows:
2
a. members appointed from Districts 1 and 3 shall serve
3 until July 1, 2008,
4 b. members appointed from Districts 2 and 4 shall serve
until July 1, 2009,
5
c. members appointed from Districts 5 and 6 shall serve
6 until July 1, 2010,
7 d. the real estate broker member shall serve until July
1, 2010,
8
e. the attorney member shall serve until July 1, 2009,
9 and
10 f. the bank officer member shall serve until July 1,
2010; and
11
2. Thereafter, all members shall serve four-year terms.
12
F. Each member shall hold office until the expiration of the
13 term of office for which appointed or until a successor has been
appointed and confirmed:
14
1. Vacancies on the Board due to death, resignation, or removal
15 occurring during a term shall be filled by the Governor for the
unexpired portion of the term in a manner as provided for regular
16 appointments to the Board;
17 2. Members filling the remainder of an unexpired term shall
assume office immediately upon appointment by the Governor and shall
18 serve until confirmation or denial of confirmation by the Senate;
and
19
3. A member may be reappointed to the Board, but shall not
20 serve more than two consecutive terms. A member that has previously
served two consecutive terms may be reappointed after the expiration
21 of at least one full term.
22 G. Members of the Board shall receive no salary or compensation
for service on the Board, but shall be reimbursed for travel
23 expenses incurred on behalf of their service on the Board pursuant
to the State Travel Reimbursement Act.
24
Req. No. 17604 Page 7

1 H. Members may be removed from office by the Governor:
2 1. For inefficiency, neglect of duty, or malfeasance in office
in the manner provided for by law for the removal of officers not
3 subject to impeachment;
4 2. For cause which shall include, but not be limited to:
5 a. the member has ceased to be qualified. A member of
the Board is no longer qualified to serve if that
6 member:
7 (1) is a member whose Certificate of Authority,
license, or permit pursuant to the laws of this
8 state has become void or has been revoked or
suspended, or
9
(2) is a member who has moved from this state,
10
b. the member has been convicted, pled guilty or nolo
11 contendere to a felony pursuant to the laws of the
United States or any jurisdiction,
12
c. the member has become medically incapacitated as
13 determined in writing by a medical doctor upon request
by the Board, or
14
d. the member has been absent from three meetings, or is
15 absent for more than one-half (1/2) the number of
minutes for which a meeting is conducted of three
16 meetings as determined by the Board during any twelve-
month period, unless such absence is determined to be
17 unavoidable in the opinion of a majority of the
remaining members;
18
3. Upon being found guilty, through due process, of
19 malfeasance, misfeasance or nonfeasance in relation to Board duties;
or
20
4. Upon being found mentally incompetent by a court of
21 competent jurisdiction.
22 I. Removal pursuant to the provisions of subsection H of this
section shall be accomplished in the following manner:
23
1. After a majority vote of the remaining members setting out
24 the dates of absences or other grounds for removal and the fact of
Req. No. 17604 Page 8

1 the disqualification of the member, a written notification of the
said vote shall be sent to the Governor; and
2
2. Upon receipt of the written notification, the Governor,
3 after a hearing conducted in accordance with the provisions of the
Administrative Procedures Act, may remove any member of the Board
4 for any of the reasons set out in the notice from the Board or for
any other reason specified in this act, provided:
5
a. removal pursuant to the provisions of this subsection
6 shall occur upon the Governor filing a written
statement of findings after the hearing as to the
7 reasons and basis for removal of the member with the
secretary of the Board, and
8
b. the Governor shall appoint another member in the
9 manner provided for appointments to the Board.
10 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 3A O.S. 2021, Section 604.1, as
amended by Section 1, Chapter 75, O.S.L. 2024 (3A O.S. Supp. 2025,
11 Section 604.1), is amended to read as follows:
12 Section 604.1. A. There is hereby re-created, until July 1,
2027, in accordance with the Oklahoma Sunset Law, the Oklahoma State
13 Athletic Commission, which shall be composed of nine (9) members
appointed by the Governor with the advice and consent of the Senate.
14 The member of the Commission initially appointed pursuant to this
act shall serve a term of three (3) years that shall expire on June
15 30, 2006. Members appointed to the Commission shall serve for terms
of three (3) years. Terms of office shall expire on June 30. All
16 vacancies and unexpired terms shall be filled in the same manner as
the original appointment and within sixty (60) days from the date of
17 the vacancy. Members may be removed by the Governor for
incompetence, willful neglect of duty, corruption in office, or
18 malfeasance in office.
19 B. Members appointed to the Commission shall reside in this
state and shall have the following qualifications:
20
1. Two members shall have experience as a professional
21 combative sports practitioner, other than as a professional wrestler
or in professional combative sports promotions;
22
2. One member shall have experience as a professional wrestler
23 or in professional wrestling promotions;
24 3. One member shall have experience in sports medicine;
Req. No. 17604 Page 9

1
4. One member shall have experience in the cable television
2 business; and
3 5. Four members shall represent the public at large as lay
members.
4
C. No member of the Commission or any person related to a
5 member within the third degree by consanguinity or affinity shall
promote, sponsor, or have any financial interest in the promotion or
6 sponsorship of any professional combative sports event or amateur
mixed martial arts event while a member of the Commission.
7
D. The members of the Commission shall elect from their
8 membership a chair and vice-chair to serve for one-year terms. A
majority of the members shall constitute a quorum for the purpose of
9 conducting the business of the Commission. The Commission shall
meet at least quarterly, and special meetings may be called by the
10 chair.
11 E. The Commission shall comply with the provisions of the
Oklahoma Open Meeting Act, the Oklahoma Open Records Act, and the
12 Administrative Procedures Act.
13 F. All members of the Commission and such employees as
determined by the Commission shall be bonded as required by Sections
14 85.58Q through 85.58V of Title 74 of the Oklahoma Statutes.
15 G. Members of the Commission shall serve without compensation
but shall be reimbursed for expenses incurred in the performance of
16 their duties as provided in the State Travel Reimbursement Act.
17 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY Section 1, Chapter 345, O.S.L.
2025 (10 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 461), is amended to read as
18 follows:
19 Section 461. A. 1. There is hereby created, until November 1,
2028, in accordance with the Oklahoma Sunset Law, the Teacher
20 Recruitment and Retention Program to be administered by Oklahoma
Partnership for School Readiness under the direction of the
21 Department of Human Services.
22 2. The Department of Human Services shall promulgate rules as
necessary to implement and enforce the provisions of this section,
23 including verifying income eligibility, employment status, and
administering subsidy benefits accordingly.
24
Req. No. 17604 Page 10

1 B. The Teacher Recruitment and Retention Program, administered
through Oklahoma Partnership for School Readiness, shall ensure
2 that:
3 1. A child care employee working at a child care facility
licensed pursuant to the Oklahoma Child Care Facilities Licensing
4 Act shall be eligible for the Teacher Recruitment and Retention
Program, provided that:
5
a. total annual gross household income does not exceed
6 One Hundred Twenty Thousand Dollars ($120,000.00) for
a two-parent household,
7
b. total annual gross household income does not exceed
8 Sixty Thousand Dollars ($60,000.00) for a single-
parent household, or
9
c. children must attend a program participating in the
10 Department of Human Services' Child Care Subsidy
Program;
11
2. As used in this section, "child care employee" shall mean
12 any individual who is employed for a minimum of twenty (20) hours
per week, averaged monthly, who provides direct care, supervision or
13 educational services to children or who performs duties on-site that
support the daily operation of the facility participating in the
14 Child Care Subsidy Program and which is licensed pursuant to the
Oklahoma Child Care Facilities Licensing Act;
15
3. An employee who qualifies under the household income
16 limitations in paragraph 1 of this subsection:
17 a. shall have household income exempted from
consideration solely for purposes of calculating cost-
18 sharing or co-payment responsibilities,
19 b. shall have co-payments waived if eligible under the
Department's Child Care Subsidy Program, and
20
c. shall be eligible to participate in the Teacher
21 Recruitment and Retention Program, even if his or her
income exceeds the Child Care Subsidy Program
22 requirements;
23 4. When an employee who is employed by a licensed child care
facility leaves employment of the licensed provider, the provider
24 shall provide written notice within thirty (30) days to the
Req. No. 17604 Page 11

1 Depa rtment of Human Services that the employee is no longer
employed; and
2
5. Other than the income exemption pursuant to paragraph 1 of
3 this subsection and the reporting requirements established pursuant
to this subsection, all other conditions of eligibility for the
4 Child Care Subsidy Program located in Oklahoma Administrative Code
(OAC) 340:40-7-1 shall be followed.
5
C. Subsection B of this section shall not apply to employees
6 who are employed by a child care facility licensed pursuant to the
Oklahoma Child Care Facilities Licensing Act and who are eligible
7 for the Child Care Subsidy Program without household income being
exempted.
8
D. The Department of Human Services shall waive co-payments for
9 employees who are employed by a licensed child care facility and who
qualify under income eligibility requirements of the Child Care
10 Subsidy Program.
