21 Indian Education, appointed by the Governor;
22 4. Two members who shall represent two different statewide
organizations representing public school teachers, appointed by the
23 President Pro Tempore of the Senate;
24
Req. No. 17604 Page 58

1 5. One member who shall represent a statewide organization
representing public school superintendents, appointed by the Speaker
2 of the House of Representatives;
3 6. One member who shall represent Oklahoma tribal colleges,
appointed by the Chancellor of Higher Education;
4
7. The Director of the Native American Cultural and Educational
5 Authority, or designee;
6 8. The Chancellor of Higher Education, or designee;
7 9. The Director of the Oklahoma Department of Career and
Technology Education, or designee; and
8
10. The Superintendent of Public Instruction, or designee.
9
D. Appointments to the Council shall be made by September 1,
10 2023. The first meeting of the Council shall be called by the
Superintendent of Public Instruction. At the first meeting, the
11 members of the Council shall elect a chair and vice chair from among
the members. Meetings of the Council shall be held at least
12 quarterly at the call of the chair. Members shall serve at the
pleasure of their appointing authorities. A majority of the members
13 of the Council shall constitute a quorum to transact business, but
no vacancy shall impair the right of the remaining members to
14 exercise all of the powers of the Council. A vacancy on the Council
shall be filled by the original appointing authority. A vacancy on
15 the Council in a seat representing an Indian tribe in the state or
the tribal education department of an Indian tribe in the state may
16 be filled by the original appointing authority from a list of
nominations submitted by the elected executive leaders of Indian
17 tribes in the state. Appointments to fill any vacancy on the
Council shall be made within three (3) months following the vacancy.
18 The State Department of Education, Oklahoma Department of Career and
Technology Education, and the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher
19 Education shall provide staff, support, and information as requested
by the Council.
20
E. Members of the Council shall receive no compensation for
21 serving on the Council but shall receive travel reimbursement as
follows:
22
1. State employees who are members of the Council shall be
23 reimbursed for travel expenses incurred in the performance of their
duties by their respective agencies in accordance with the State
24 Travel Reimbursement Act; and
Req. No. 17604 Page 59

1
2. All other members of the Council shall be reimbursed by the
2 Office of Management and Enterprise Services for travel expenses
incurred in the performance of their duties in accordance with the
3 State Travel Reimbursement Act.
4 F. The Council shall act in accordance with the provisions of
the Oklahoma Open Meeting Act and the Oklahoma Open Records Act.
5
G. Members who serve on the Council shall be exempt from the
6 dual-office-holding prohibitions of Section 6 of Title 51 of the
Oklahoma Statutes.
7
H. The Council shall have the following duties:
8
1. Identify strategies for developing an efficient and reliable
9 process of communications between Oklahoma education entities,
educators, tribal organizations, and other interested parties;
10
2. Identify and disseminate research-based, measurable
11 criteria, both behavioral and academic, by which the success and
efficacy of the education offered to Native American students in
12 Oklahoma may be measured;
13 3. Analyze data to ensure that education agencies in Oklahoma
continue to address the education needs of Native American students;
14
4. Encourage and promote Native American educational leadership
15 at all levels of the education system; and
16 5. Make recommendations to the State Board of Education for
programs that will help achieve the purposes of the Oklahoma
17 Advisory Council on Indian Education Act.
18 I. The Council shall evaluate and make an annual report on the
effectiveness of the public education system in Oklahoma in meeting
19 the needs of Native American students in Oklahoma. The report shall
be submitted to the State Board of Education. The report shall also
20 contain a summary of the findings made by the Council pursuant to
subsection H of this section, a summary of all data collected by the
21 Council, a summary of the means by which all data was collected by
the Council, and any other information deemed necessary by the
22 Council.
23 SECTION 32. AMENDATORY 70 O.S. 2021, Section 23-105, as
amended by Section 1, Chapter 296, O.S.L. 2023 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025,
24 Section 23-105), is amended to read as follows:
Req. No. 17604 Page 60

1
Section 23-105. There is hereby re-created, to continue until
2 July 1, 2026, in accordance with the provisions of the Oklahoma
Sunset Law, Section 3901 et seq. of Title 74 of the Oklahoma
3 Statutes, a body corporate and politic to be known as the "Oklahoma
Educational Television Authority", and by that name the Authority
4 may sue and be sued, and plead and be impleaded. The Authority is
hereby constituted an instrumentality of the state, and the exercise
5 by the Authority of the powers conferred by this article for the
planning, construction, operation, and maintenance of educational
6 television facilities shall be deemed and held to be an essential
function of the state.
7
The Oklahoma Educational Television Authority shall consist of
8 thirteen (13) members, including the President of the University of
Oklahoma, the President of Oklahoma State University, the State
9 Superintendent of Public Instruction, the Chancellor of the Oklahoma
State Regents for Higher Education, the president of one of the
10 state-supported four-year colleges to be chosen by the presidents of
this group of institutions, the president of one of the state-
11 supported two-year colleges to be chosen by the presidents of this
group of institutions, and seven additional members to be appointed
12 by the Governor with the advice and consent of the Senate, to serve
seven-year terms.
13
The appointed members shall have been residents of the state for
14 at least five (5) years preceding the date of their appointment.
The appointed members shall include one member from each of the
15 congressional districts and any remaining members shall be appointed
from the state at large. However, when congressional districts are
16 redrawn each member appointed prior to July 1 of the year in which
such modification becomes effective shall complete the current term
17 of office and appointments made after July 1 of the year in which
such modification becomes effective shall be based on the redrawn
18 districts. Appointments made after July 1 of the year in which such
modification becomes effective shall be from any redrawn districts
19 which are not represented by an authority member until such time as
each of the modified congressional districts are represented by an
20 authority member. A majority of the appointed members shall be
actively engaged in the profession of education. Each appointed
21 member of the Authority, before entering upon the duties of the
member, shall take the oath provided for by Section 1 of Article XV
22 of the Constitution of the State of Oklahoma.
23 The seven original members appointed by the Governor shall
continue in office for terms expiring on June 30, 1954; June 30,
24 1955; June 30, 1956; June 30, 1957; June 30, 1958; June 30, 1959;
Req. No. 17604 Page 61

1 and June 30, 1960, respectively. The terms of each of the original
appointed members shall be designated by the Governor, and said
2 members shall serve for their appointed terms and until their
respective successors shall be appointed and qualified. The
3 successor of each appointed member shall be appointed for a term of
seven (7) years, except that any person appointed to fill a vacancy
4 shall be appointed to serve only for the unexpired term in said
vacancy.
5
The Authority shall elect from the membership of the Authority a
6 chair, a vice-chair, and a secretary-treasurer. Any such officers
elected by the Authority on or after July 1, 1984, shall be
7 appointed to serve a term of one (1) year. Seven members of the
Authority shall constitute a quorum, and the vote of seven members
8 shall be necessary for any action taken by the Authority. No
vacancy in the membership of the Authority shall impair the right of
9 a quorum to exercise all the rights and perform all the duties of
the Authority. The Authority shall meet at least quarterly.
10
The members of the Authority shall not be entitled to
11 compensation for their services, but each member shall be reimbursed
for travel expenses incurred in performing official duties in
12 accordance with the provisions of the State Travel Reimbursement
Act. No liability or obligation shall be incurred by the Authority
13 beyond the extent to which monies shall have been provided pursuant
to the authority of this article.
14
